<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP MUSIC REVIEWS; PHIL COLLINS: AS ALWAYS, THE EVERYGUY OF POP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHUCK CRISAFULLI, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Over the last 25 years, Phil Collins has undergone one of the odder 
transformations in pop music. He began his career drumming with Genesis when 
the band was led by Peter Gabriel and was considered one of the headier British 
art-rock outfits. Collins since has become a mega-successful mainstream 
crooner. 
</P>
<P>
 With more than 35 million records sold and a half-dozen Grammys collected for 
his post-Genesis work, Collins doesn't have many pop summits left to conquer. 
He does, however, have plenty of fans to entertain and, on Monday at the Forum, 
dependable entertainment value is what they got from the affable singer, who 
plays Irvine Meadows tonight. 
</P>
<P>
 In a pair of sets that added up to nearly three hours of sturdily constructed, 
energetically delivered pop tunes, Collins demonstrated that even though it has 
been four years since his last tour, he is still a consummate crowd-pleaser. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 On a stage resembling a kind of quaint urban wasteland complete with blazing 
trash can, changeable billboard and sparking elevated train, he ambled about 
and led his four-piece band through all the hits and a good deal of new 
material. Though his muse has long been anchored in the mainstream, and 
predictable showmanship has superseded any spontaneity in the music, his 
cheerful stage presence kept the show rolling forward. 
</P>
<P>
 He played a couple of songs on the piano and sat down at an extra set of drums 
just in time to play the thundering signature fill during "In the Air Tonight." 
He belted out such heartfelt confessionals as "Take a Look at Me Now" with 
straightforward intensity, and between songs he was like a cheeky music-hall 
comedian, winning over the crowd with slightly risque monologues.  
</P>
<P>
 His band was perfectly polished, entirely competent and almost completely 
without soul. The singer alone gave the music some heart. Collins' voice is not 
commanding but he pulled emotional nuances out of his tales of fractured 
romance and unrequited love, and added pep to the upbeat numbers in the second 
set. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Collins is the pop star as Everyguy. His guileless approach to his craft and 
his willingness to poke fun at himself and his non-matinee idol looks combine 
to make him one of the more likable and less lordly of pop luminaries. His 
down-to-earth manner prevails when his material nears mawkishness, and even his 
clunky version of "You Can't Hurry Love" becomes easier to take when you see 
what a good time he has singing it. 
</P>
<P>
 * Phil Collins sings tonight at 8 at the Irvine Meadows Amphitheatre, 8800 
Irvine Center Drive, Irvine. $25-$52.50. (714) 740-2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
