speed bumps -- from "judder bars" to "sleeping policeman" -- we get a bit of 
history from Keith Stark of Alhambra. 
</P>
<P>
 "In the days of horse-drawn wagons, they were used in hilly country to provide 
support for the wagon wheels while giving the horses a chance for a few 
moments' rest," Stark writes. "They were then called 'thank-you-ma'ams' (the 
horses' unspoken expression of gratitude)." 
</P>
