<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Adrianne Goodman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 WHAT STRIKE? Baseball strike or no (A1), business is in full swing at some 
Ventura County sports bars, where spectators are finding no shortage of other 
games to watch. The NFL preseason has already started, and bar owners say 
football fans who frequent local watering holes outnumber baseball fans anyway. 
"The only time you get interest in baseball is during the World Series," said 
John Vanderwall, owner of the Tree House Sports Bar & Grill in Simi Valley. As 
for the strike, he said: "It won't hurt my business at all." 
</P>
<P>
 IT'S THE PRINCIPLE: State Sen. Gary K. Hart (D-Santa Barbara) has received the 
1994 Integrity Award from California Common Cause for "adhering to ethical 
principles." Hart shares the award with Republican state Sen. Marian Bergeson 
of Newport Beach. . . . The honor has been bestowed only once before, in 1992, 
when the watchdog group started the awards program. Hart "exemplifies what a 
public servant should be," said Executive Director Ruth Holton.  
</P>
<P>
 ROAD WORK: Ventura County construction crews are moving forward with the final 
phase of a construction project on Santa Rosa Road, based on findings that most 
of the artifacts at a Chumash burial site there were removed years ago (B1). . 
. . Work on a portion of the project was halted last year after bone fragments 
were discovered. "All in all, we're happy with the way things are going," said 
county official W. Butch Britt. "The end result will be a better and safer 
road." 
</P>
<P>
 HARD AT PLAY: A fierce game of Scrabble is not for the faint of heart. Just 
ask Joyce Frasco of Moorpark, who will compete this weekend in the National 
Scrabble Championships at Universal City. . . . Frasco, 64, once ranked at the 
expert level in competition, but is playing fewer games these days and has 
dropped down a notch. Top-ranked Scrabblers play at least 10 games a week and 
spend hours memorizing word lists. Bluffing and cagey strategy also come in 
handy. "It's not a casual game," Frasco said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
