<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY BRIEFLY: LONG BEACH INVESTOR BUYS AIRPORTER GARDEN HOTEL IN 
IRVINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mike C. Wang, a 30-year-old Long Beach real estate investor, has purchased the 
214-room Airporter Garden Hotel in Irvine for $10 million, his first real 
estate purchase in Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
 Wang, president of the hotel division of Wang Partnership in Long Beach, said 
the hotel, at 18700 MacArthur Blvd. directly across from John Wayne Airport, is 
undergoing a $4-million renovation to be completed next month. 
</P>
<P>
 The hotel was purchased from the Duffy family, which had owned and operated it 
for more than 20 years.  
</P>
<P>
 "We wanted a location by an airport in an upscale city, and Irvine fit the 
bill," Wang said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Airporter is the fifth hotel Wang has purchased through his partnership. 
He owns hotels in Southern California and in Colorado. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA081294-0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 069371 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
August 12, 1994, Friday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 7; Column 2; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
202 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Comarco Inc.: The Yorba Linda-based company said Thursday that it has acquired 
privately held software developer LCTI in Gaithersburg, Md. The company, with 
revenue of about $1.5 million a year, sells proprietary software used in the 
automated test system market. 
</P>
<P>
 Terms of the deal were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
 Comarco has been an LCTI customer in the past, buying its software to use in 
development of test programs for the U.S. Navy. Comarco provides wireless 
communications products, engineering services and facility management services 
to government and commercial clients. 
</P>
<P>
 Test systems are the computers that run tests on complex electronic equipment 
-- from television sets to the navigation equipment on an aircraft carrier. 
LCTI was founded in 1990 to design a product to streamline the process of 
programming and documenting the software for electronic test systems. 
</P>
<P>
 It first sold its product to the U.S. Army in 1991, and all branches of the 
military have since purchased it. Commercial applications focus on the airline 
community, telecommunications and the medical and biotechnology industries. 
</P>
<P>
 The company will be operated as a separate unit of Comarco, said Don M. 
Bailey, Comarco president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
